The numbers blur into a rhythmic, mechanical grinding, like an old-fashioned cash register tape printing out failed transactions. I pause, letting the mental chatter fade into that hollow, repetitive sound.  It’s not just the rejection of candidates; it’s the sheer *weight* of the arithmetic, the way each number has to be pried open, its prime factors examined like a suspect’s alibi, before it can even be considered for the final check.

I look at the list of what I have. Two, eight, and two hundred forty-two. They feel sparse. Too sparse. If this is a natural phenomenon, surely there should be more density, or at least a pattern I can see without calculating every single square sum up to infinity. But the constraint $n \ge r(n)$ is brutal. It cuts the search space in half immediately, and then the prime factorization filter cuts it down to a thread. And then the reverse function, that chaotic, non-linear beast, has to align perfectly with the difference of two squares. It’s like trying to balance a coin on its edge while walking a tightrope.

I wonder if 242 is an anomaly, or if it’s the start of a sequence. Palindromes of the form $2k^2$. $2 \times 1^2 = 2$. $2 \times 2^2 = 8$. $2 \times 11^2 = 242$. What about $2 \times 22^2$? $2 \times 484 = 968$. Is 968 a palindrome? No. $2 \times 33^2 = 2 \times 1089 = 2178$. No. $2 \times 44^2 = 2 \times 1936 = 3872$. No. $2 \times 55^2 = 2 \times 3025 = 6050$. No. $2 \times 66^2 = 2 \times
 4356 = 8712$. No. $2 \times 77^2 = 2 \times 5929 = 11858$. No. $2 \times 88^2 = 2 \times 7744 = 15488$. No. $2 \times 99^2 = 2 \times 9801 = 19602$. No.

It seems palindromes of the form $2k^2$ are incredibly rare. Maybe 242 is the last one? Or maybe there’s a huge one further out. But I can’t check them all. The manual method is too slow. I need a different angle.

What if I look at the equation $r(n) = (a^2 - b^2)/2$? Since $n = (a^2 + b^2)/2$, and $r(n)$ is the reverse, maybe I can iterate on $a$ and $b$ instead of $n$. Pick $a$ and $b$ such that $a > b$, same parity. Calculate $n = (a^2 + b^2)/2$. Calculate $r_{req} = (a^2 - b^2)/2$. Then check if $r(n) == r_{req}$. This might be faster because I can generate $n$ directly from squares, skipping the prime factorization check entirely. The only filter is whether the reverse of the generated $n$ matches the required difference.

